Reasearch Guided Question

Does the GDP of a country affect internet prices by either increasing or decreasing it?

Origin

We have found this data on Kaggle initially, and it represents internet prices across the world ranging from 2010-2020. The data seems to originate from the City API project site, but unfortunately, we could not retrieve information regarding the data/ data collectors origins after further research. But from exploring the website https://city-api.io/en/ they seem to provide data about the worldwide related activity. They merge data sources to fit the clients pressing questions. Some of the features are paid, but our data related to worldwide internet prices is free. This data was collected to show a trend in internet prices over the years spanning the entire world to notice trends in fees and other related factors. Finally, the last time the data was updated was a month ago, making the tables relatively up to date and accurate.

Importance/ Interesting to Investing

This issue, also known as the digital divide, prevents pupils from developing countries from gaining access to the Internet and from connecting in this ever-globalizing market. Many people believe that Internet access should be a fundamental human right. Everyone needs equal access to the information and opportunities available from computers connected to the Internet. Unfortunately, access to computing devices and the Internet is unevenly distributed. Some people dont have any computing devices, some have high-speed Internet on their home computers, and some are in the middle. This difference in access is the digital divide and is often due to socio-economic, geographical, or demographic factors. For example, a country like Norway has 96% citizens with internet access, while Somalia has merely 2% of the population. Hence it is essential to witness a thorough correlation analysis to see how internet prices and GDP plays a role. We chose GDP as our second data set as we see a general trend with countries with higher GDP having accessibility to the Internet while developing countries experience the opposite.

Technical challenge

Before reaching our visual portion of the project, one of our biggest challenges was our difficulty joining the GDP and Internet prices table. Many of the country names didnt precisely match to join, causing some challenges in understanding and manipulating our data. Within our EDA, we had to manually rename all countries that had different spelling physically, were abbreviated, or were conflicting territories not recognized in a table. One specific country we came across a technical problem with was China. As there are a lot of conflicting regions and since only one internet price was labeled for the country, our only solution was to combine Hong Kong SAR, China and Macao SAR, China. We manually fixed this case as there was no alternative option. So we combined the GDP of all three territories and evaluated it as one case, The Peoples Republic of China. In the end, although we didnt encounter any difficult technical situations, this was an obstacle that we had to work around as independent data collectors may have different views on territorial concerns.

Conclusion

Our main goal was to witness a correlation between GDP and Internet prices. In our visualization section, we started by making a leaflet map to see the spread and distribution of GDP in the world see higher GDP in European countries and lower GDP in African countries. After we saw the nations, we began to compare GDP to Internet prices in the following year: 2010, 2011, 2014, and 2018. Finally, after choosing 35 random countries worldwide, we used geom_point to note them and geom_smooth to witness a trend. From our conclusion, we can state that during years of 2010, 2011, 2014 and 2018 we are witnessing positive correlation between the countrys gross domestic product and countrys average internet price.
